Determine the Likelihood of HarmThe likelihood of harm is the product of value items 5 & 6 for each of the categories:Note: A risk with a high probability and severe consequence has more likelihood of harm than risk with a low probability and moderate or low consequence.8. Emergency Equipment with Adequate Controls - 2 c. Additional Controls Required - 19. AssessmentEvaluate the Level of Risk and whether the equipment is Critical or not by dividing the Likelihood of Harm by the score for Level of Control:AValue is 100 or lessEquipment is not CriticalBValue is more than 100Equipment is CriticalCValue is 100 or less but Equipment is DPRelatedEquipment is DP Critical10. Evaluation of Environmentally Critical equipmentAny equipment the failure of which causes a direct impact on the environment is to be considered as ‘Environmentally Critical Equipment’.6.5DRY DOCKING / REPAIRSAs per the class requirement, dry-docking of the vessels shall be carried out at the stipulated period. In addition a vessel may have toundergo repairs at shipyard, lay berth or anchorage due to damage suffered by the vessel, to address any defects / deficiencies or formajor modifications.The running list of dry dock jobs are to be maintained in PMS from the time of completion of one dry docking till the next dry docking.The Dry Docking module in Phoenix may be used by the superintendent to assist with the Dry docking / repair process.The flow chart below explains the process to be followed.
